A study on contraceptive habits among Portuguese women revealed that 16% of sexually active girls aged 15-19 do not use birth control.
Despite receiving contraceptive information in school, many young women still engage in risky behavior.
The morning-after pill is popular among this demographic, sparking controversy in Peru over its distribution.
Critics fear easier access may promote promiscuity, but research suggests otherwise.
The debate extends to the US, where emergency contraception faces restrictions and moral objections.
Ultimately, the issue of reproductive rights remains contentious, with conflicting views on abortion and contraception prevailing.
